##
## librarian
##
@node librarian "Librarian = Rexecute Object Module Librarian"

 The librarian is a CLI ONLY utility that updates and maintains your link
 libraries.

	Useage:
		LIBRARIAN option library filelist

	Where OPTION may be one of the following:

	L	=  List library contents including size

	D	=  Delete object modules from library

	R	=  Replace object modules (or add if not defined)

	F	=  File dump of module in ASCII format (ie. disassembled)

	S	=  Screen dump of module in ASCII format (ie. disassembled)

	X	=  Xtract module from library

	C	=  Copy and dump library module( no delete )

	LIBRARY =  The name of the library file to be created or modified.
		   If no ".lib" extension is provided on the command line,
		   it is appended.

   	FILELIST=  A list of object module filenames separated by spaces.
		   Note that if ".o" is not present in the filenames,
   		   it will be appended.

 An example would be something like:

 librarian r Rexecute:lib/mylib.lib Rexecute:objectfiles/findlib ram:addlib ram:del

 The above would add findlib.o addlib.o & del.o to the link library
 mylib.lib in the LIB directory within the assigned Rexecute: volume.

 You can get a reminder of the above template by typing the standard
 "librarian ?" at the cli prompt.

@endnode

##
##disexec
##
@node disexec "DISExec, Executable disassembler."

 DISExec allows you to disassemble an Rexecute derived executable file to
 produce an ARexx script, You may then edit or do as you like with this
 file before recompiling etc.

 This utlity may be used from Cli or Workbench, With or without arguments,

 From CLI the template is:

 DISExec [executable] [output_file]

 If any arguments are missing, A filerequestor will prompt you for either
 of the file names.

 You may get a usage template by the usual DISExec ?

 From WorkBench, You can SHIFT select the executable file you wish to
 disassemble, Failing this, A filerequestor will prompt you for the
 executable, You will be asked via a filerequestor for the destination
 of the output file.

 The executable is checked to ensure that it is an Rexecute derived
 executable, If that is so, it is disassembled to the output file with a
 header that describes where the file came from & the version string ( if
 present ).
 An icon is also written out ( Which looks remarkably similar to the icon
 that is saved by Rexecute when you compile with the script option! ).

 The Default tool in this icon is set to "C:ED".

 You finally get notification that the disassembly is complete.


@endnode

##
## what's the advantage
##
@node advantage "Why should I use Rexecute ?"

 The first thought that you may have had when seeing Rexecute advertised
 as an Arexx compiler may have been "Great!, I can create executables"
 However, The advantages to using Rexecute do not stop there.

 The main advantage is the use of @{ " link libraries " link linklibs } for commonly used
 routines that can be brought into your program with the use of the pre
 compiler directive `#extern'.
 If you use the Arexx version of such libraries as the ARP.library, you
 will find it easier to Write external functions for the checking and
 loading of such libraries and also the more frequently used library
 functions.
 Making heavy use of this feature alone should reduce development time
 considerably.

 You no longer need to add trace or interrupt options to your source code
 as these can be added at compile time ( and just as easily removed by re-
 compiling with trace and interrupt options disabled, Which is actually
 quicker than removal of statements from your source code using a text
 editor !)

 AH, BUT I DON'T WISH TO PRODUCE EXECUTABLE FILES, WHAT DO I GET OUT OF IT?

 Quite a lot actually, You will still enjoy all the benefits of Rexecute as
 you can choose to produce a @{ " SCRIPT " link shortcuts } instead of an executable, Rexecute
 will insert into the script ALL that would have gone into an executable,
 including declared external procedures ( or functions, depending on how
 you think of them! ) with trace and interrupt options added etc, plus of
 course, the stripping of ALL comments from the source file, sometimes
 reducing the overall size of the file considerably.

 If you program using C or assembler, You can add your compiled script
 to a program and execute it as an Arexx command string.


 Most compilers enable the written program to run faster than in its
 interpreted form, I'm afraid that Rexecute does not, at least not
 intentionaly although there may be a slight increase due to the fact that
 the compiled file does not contain ANY comments at all and therefore there
 is no time wasted in parsing.

@endnode

##
## cmdshell
##
@node cmdshell "Using the Command Shell..."

 The shell window is initiated using the @{ " New Cli " link shell } menu option.
 Providing that Arexx is available and running, The shell window that will
 appear will be a COMMAND shell, This means that you may use the
 Rexecute Arexx Commands directly within the shell, Although many of the
 commands may not appear to be of use whilst the Main Panel is available,

 You may amend the preferences that are set within the icon tooltypes.
 For example, Once you have started Rexecute, you may wish to change the
 tooltype TEMP_FILE to another destination. ( This does not amend the
 tooltype value within the icon, Simply the value that is used within
 that session. )

 If the command you typed in is not recognised by Rexecute, The command
 shell will then attempt to launch it as a STANDARD Arexx script, if that
 fails, the command shell will attempt to launch it as a DOS command.
 Should this fail, It finally gives up and will give you the error
 message: <COMMAND> Not found!

 NOTE:	The arexx script that will be looked for during the SECOND stage
 of the above paragraph will be a STANDARD Arexx script ending in ".rexx"
 as oppposed to an Rexecute macro which ends in ".rx". An Rexecute macro is
 launched with the arexx command "launchmacro <macroname>".

 If you are using a PAL system, You will find that the shell window will
 Open below the Rexecute Main Panel allowing you to see any changes or
 updates, If you are using LESS than 256 scan lines, The shell may cover
 the bottom of the Main Panel Window.

 The Command Shell is actually implemented as a Rexecute Arexx macro!,
 which can be found within the directory "Rexecute:Support/" You can of
 course compile this file and use the executable verion to control Rexecute
 from outside if Rexecute has been started with the "R" option.
 You can of course edit the CmdSHELL.rx file if it does not meet with
 your requirements, Although I do recommend that you only edit a backup
 of the file!.

 If you are using a floppy based system, you may find it a bit tedious
 waiting for the CmdShell to load and sort itself out, You can cut down
 on this time by editing the CmdSHELL.rx file and removing the help
 system, Only do this on a backup!
 OR
 Rename the file CmdSHELL.rx to something else, Then rename CmdSHELL.crip
 to CmdSHELL.rx. ( This effectively does the above for you )

@endnode

##
## cmdline
##
@node cmdline "Command Line Options"

 You have several options avilable to you from the command line,
 Using "Rexecute ?" will produce the following:

Usage:
	Rexecute [R] [?] [File] [File] [File] etc...

Where:
	R 	= ARexx only, NO interface, Although the GUI can be popped
		  from an ARexx script with the appropriate command.

	?	= Help, Prints the argument template to screen, like this!

	File	= File to be processed, if R has been given, These files
		  are assumed to be Rexecute ARexx scripts and are processed
		  systematically,If no `R' was given, it is assumed that
		  the given files are scripts to be compiled. (This uses
		  the values in the preferences to compile, ie. icon,
		  version etc.
		  No arguments following Rexecute will cause Rexecute to simply
		  Open it's Main Panel, check the preferences and then
		  await further input.


 Example Rexecute Cli startups:

 ENTERED:
 Rexecute work:test.rexx work:status.rexx rexx:marquis.rexx

 RESULT:
 Rexecute will compile each argument successively and will exit after the
 last compilation  ( Using the default preferences )

 ENTERED:
 Rexecute R

 RESULT:
 Rexecute will initialise itself in REXX ONLY status, i.e. NO GUI although
 a GUI (Iconified or Main Panel Window) may be opened with the Arexx
 command "iconify" or "opengui" respectively.

 ENTERED:
 Rexecute R setup.rx compilecurrent.rx newproject.rx openwindows.rx

 RESULT:
 Rexecute will initialise itself in a REXX ONLY status and will then process
 each argument as an Rexecute Arexx macro.
 Once finished, Rexecute will remain running in a REXX ONLY state unless
 a) A GUI has been opened with the relative command from within a macro.
 b) The command "QUIT" has been issued from one of the macros ( this will
    not take effect until the LAST macro has been processed )

 Multiple compilations can of course be started from @{ " WorkBench " link wbstartup }.

@endnode

##
##wbstartup
##
@node wbstartup "Starting Rexecute from the WorkBench..."

 Rexecute can be started by simply double clicking the icon, This starts
 Rexecute which will intialise itself, load the preferences, Open the Main
 Panel and the await further instructions.

 You can automatically compile multiple source files by the use of multiple
 selection from the WorkBench, i.e. Click once on Rexecute, Then whilst
 holding down the shift key, click on any source files you may wish compiled
 and double clicking on the last one. ( Check your Amiga User Manual for a
 more comprehensive description of multiple selection ).
 No interface will show and Rexecute will automatically clean up and exit
 after the last file has been compiled.

 NOTE: The above method will cause the files to be compiled with the
 preferences that are in the default settings.

@endnode

##
##arexx
##
@node arexx "Rexecute's Arexx Interface"

 Rexecute's Arexx port is named "REXECUTE"

 The compiled programs will have their own Arexx port and will be named
 after themselves, i.e. if you compiled Marquis.rexx into Marquis, It
 would have its own port by the name of MARQUIS.

 Rexecute has a list of over 75 Arexx commands which cover practically ALL
 operations and enable Rexecute to be a competent HOST as well as an
 accomplished SERVER.
 These Commands may be sent via a script, macro or directly addressed
 through the use of the CmdSHELL. ( If using the CmdSHELL, you can get
 information and a usage template by simply typing HELP <COMMAND> providing
 you haven't decided to use the cut down version of the CmdSHELL)

 		Arexx Commands by subject:

		@{ " Main command selection " link miscrxx }
		@{ " Interrupt command's    " link intcom }
		@{ " Trace command's        " link tracecom }
		@{ " Argument command's     " link argcom }

@endnode

##
##miscrxx
##
@node miscrxx "Miscelaneous Rexx commands..."

 These commands cover a wide range of subjects and uses...

	COMMAND:	LOCK
	DESCRIPTION:	LOCK grants you exclusive access to Rexecutes Arexx
			commands
	USAGE:		LOCK


	COMMAND:	UNLOCK
	DESCRIPTION:	UNLOCK releases exclusive access to Rexecutes Arexx
			commands
	USAGE:		UNLOCK

	COMMAND:	QUIT
	DESCRIPTION:	QUIT shuts down Rexecute, if QUIT_REQUEST is FALSE,
			you will not be prompted as to whether you wish
			to quit or not
	USAGE:		QUIT

	COMMAND:	ICONIFY
	DESCRIPTION:	This switches Rexecute to an Iconified state.
	USAGE:		ICONIFY

	COMMAND:	OPENGUI
	DESCRIPTION:	This switches Rexecute to the main interface panel.
	USAGE:		OPENGUI

	COMMAND:	REXXONLY
	DESCRIPTION:	This closes all visible signs of Rexecute, access
			can only be through the Arexx port, which is named
			REXECUTE.
	USAGE:		REXXONLY

	COMMAND:	TELL
	DESCRIPTION:	TELL will pass on information to the user, but ONLY
			if the verbose variable has been set to TRUE.
	USAGE:		TELL <string>

	COMMAND:	SHOUT
	DESCRIPTION:	SHOUT will inform the user and does not use the
			verbose variable. Used for error reporting etc.
	USAGE:		SHOUT <string>

	COMMAND:	REQUEST
	DESCRIPTION:	REQUEST will pass on information to the user via a
			system requestor. Used for urgent error messages
			that may be overlooked if put through the Rexecute
			stasis window
	USAGE:		REQUEST <string>

	COMMAND:	VERSION
	DESCRIPTION:	This sets the Rexecute variable version, Causing the
			insertion of a version string in to the compiled
			file, If there is NO argument, it is assumed to be
			TRUE.
	USAGE:		VERSION [BOOL]

	COMMAND:	VERBOSE
	DESCRIPTION:	This sets the Rexecute variable verbose, allowing the
			reporting of all actions in the Rexecute stasis window
			If there is NO argument, it is assumed to be TRUE.
	USAGE:		VERBOSE [BOOL]

	COMMAND:	RUN
	DESCRIPTION:	When set, Rexecute will run the executable after
			compilation If there is NO argument, it is assumed
			to be TRUE.
	USAGE:		RUN [BOOL]

	COMMAND:	WRITEICON
	DESCRIPTION:	When set, Rexecute will Write out icons for ALL file
			output. If there is NO argument, it is assumed to
			be TRUE.
	USAGE:		WRITEICON [BOOL]

	COMMAND:	ADDLINKLIB
	DESCRIPTION:	This will add the given link libraries to the
			list of libraries to be searched during compilation
	USAGE:		ADDLINKLIB <linklib1> [linklib2]...[linklib15]

	COMMAND:	GETLINKLIB
	DESCRIPTION:	This will allow the user to choose a link
			library via an ASL file requestor.
	USAGE:		GETLINKLIB

	COMMAND:	REMLINKLIB
	DESCRIPTION:	REMLINKLIB will remove the given link libraries
			from the list of libraries to be searched during
			compilation.
	USAGE:		REMLINKLIB <linklib1> [linklib2]......[linklib15]

	COMMAND:	RESETLIBLIST
	DESCRIPTION:	This will remove all link libraries from the list,
			freeing memory and re-initialising the list.
	USAGE:		RESETLIBLIST

	COMMAND:	SETAUTHOR
	DESCRIPTION:	SETAUTHOR determines the author string that is
			inserted in compiled scripts and also forms part of
			the version string, do NOT use any puntuation marks
			as the Dos command `VERSION' tends to terminate the
			string early if it comes across anything odd!
	USAGE:		SETAUTHOR <name string>

	COMMAND:	LOADPREFS
	DESCRIPTION:	LOADPREFS will cause Rexecute to load the prefs file
			supplied as an argument, If no argument is supplied
			A filerequestor will prompt the user.
	USAGE:		LOADPREFS [prefsfile]

	COMMAND:	SAVEPREFS
	DESCRIPTION:	This will cause Rexecute to save the preferences to
			the default prefs file which is set in Rexecute''s tool
			types.
	USAGE:		SAVEPREFS

	COMMAND:	SAVEPREFSAS
	DESCRIPTION:	SAVEPREFSAS will cause Rexecute to save the preferences
			to a file supplied as an argument,A filerequestor
			is supplied if there is no argument.
	USAGE:		SAVEPREFSAS [prefsfile]

	COMMAND:	SETOUTPUT
	DESCRIPTION:	SETOUTPUT denotes the filetype that is produced by
			Rexecute, Choice of 4 EXECUTABLE, LIBRARYOBJECT,
			LINKOBJECT & SCRIPT, if no argument is supplied,
			defaults to EXECUTABLE.
	USAGE:		SETOUTPUT [filetype]

	COMMAND:	SETDESTLIB
	DESCRIPTION:	SETDESTLIB will set the destination link library
			that the compiled object file will be added to,
			ONLY OF USE IF OUTPUT TYPE IS SET TO LIBRARY OBJECT
	USAGE:		SETDESTLIB <linklibrary>

	COMMAND:	COMPILE
	DESCRIPTION:	COMPILE sets the compilation process in motion, if
			an argument is supplied, Then this is compiled
			instead of anything that may already be set as the
			source file.
	USAGE:		COMPILE [source file]

	COMMAND:	LAUNCHMACRO
	DESCRIPTION:	LAUNCHMACRO will launch another Arexx macro
	USAGE:		LAUNCHMACRO <macro>

	COMMAND:	SETSRCFILE
	DESCRIPTION:	This sets the Rexecute source file to the argument
			supplied, if no argument is supplied, An ASL
			filerequestor will prompt the user.
	USAGE:		SETSRCFILE [file name]

	COMMAND:	SETOBJFILE
	DESCRIPTION:	This sets the Rexecute object file to the argument
			supplied, if no argument is supplied, An ASL
			filerequestor will prompt the user.
	USAGE:		SETOBJFILE [file name]

	COMMAND:	SETEXECFILE
	DESCRIPTION:	SETEXECFILE sets the Rexecute executable file to the
			argument supplied, if no argument is supplied, A
			filerequestor will prompt the user.
	USAGE:		SETEXECFILE [file name]

	COMMAND:	SETSRCDIR
	DESCRIPTION:	SETSRCDIR sets the Rexecute source directory to the
			argument supplied.
	USAGE:		SETSRCDIR <directory>

	COMMAND:	SETOBJDIR
	DESCRIPTION:	SETOBJDIR sets the Rexecute object directory to the
			argument supplied.
	USAGE:		SETOBJDIR <directory>

	COMMAND:	SETEXECDIR
	DESCRIPTION:	SETEXECDIR sets the Rexecute executable directory to
			the argument supplied.
	USAGE:		SETEXECDIR <directory>

	COMMAND:	SETLIBDIR
	DESCRIPTION:	SETLIBDIR sets the Rexecute link library directory to
			the argument supplied.
	USAGE:		SETLIBDIR <directory>

	COMMAND:	SETREADER
	DESCRIPTION:	SETREADER determines the default tool to Read the
			src file or script output.
	USAGE:		SETREADER <tool>

	COMMAND:	SETEDITOR
	DESCRIPTION:	SETEDITOR determines the default tool to Edit the
			src file or script output.
	USAGE:		SETEDITOR <tool>


@endnode

